And today, questions too.

36
00:02:06,880 --> 00:02:11,000
Shall I just fire away for the first half of the time

37
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:15,360
to give you a sense of how I see the subject,

38
00:02:15,360 --> 00:02:18,000
or at least within that limited time?

39
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:22,480
And then questions are totally welcome.

40
00:02:22,480 --> 00:02:24,640
Always welcome, actually.

41
00:02:24,640 --> 00:02:26,600
So I'll just start right up.

42
00:02:26,600 --> 00:02:31,160
So essentially, linear algebra progresses

43
00:02:31,160 --> 00:02:41,040
starting with vectors to matrices, and then finally

44
00:02:41,040 --> 00:02:42,560
to subspaces.

45
00:02:42,560 --> 00:02:46,560
So that's like the abstraction, you could say abstraction,

46
00:02:46,560 --> 00:02:50,720
but it's not difficult, that you want to see.

47
00:02:50,720 --> 00:02:53,320
Until you see the idea of a subspace,

48
00:02:53,320 --> 00:02:56,120
you haven't really got linear algebra.

49
00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:58,520
So I'll start at the beginning.

50
00:02:58,520 --> 00:03:01,240
What do you do with vectors?

51
00:03:01,240 --> 00:03:04,200
Answer, you take their linear combinations.

52
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:06,160
That's what you can do with a vector.

53
00:03:06,160 --> 00:03:11,160
You can multiply it by a number, and you can add or subtract.

54
00:03:11,160 --> 00:03:13,800
So that's the key operation.

55
00:03:13,800 --> 00:03:18,120
Suppose I have vectors u, v, and w.

56
00:03:18,120 --> 00:03:20,880
Let me take three of them.

57
00:03:20,880 --> 00:03:22,680
So I can take their combinations,

58
00:03:22,720 --> 00:03:28,640
so some combination will be, say, some number times u,

59
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:33,240
plus some number times v, plus some number times w.

60
00:03:33,240 --> 00:03:36,560
So these numbers are called scalars.

61
00:03:36,560 --> 00:03:39,760
So these would be called scalars.

62
00:03:39,760 --> 00:03:44,320
And the whole thing is a linear combination.

63
00:03:44,320 --> 00:03:48,240
Let me abbreviate those words, linear combination.

64
00:03:48,240 --> 00:03:52,120
And you get some answer, say, b.

65
00:03:53,120 --> 00:03:54,400
OK.

66
00:03:54,400 --> 00:04:00,600
But let's pin it down, make this whole discussion specific.

67
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:04,560
Yeah, I started a little early, I think.

68
00:04:04,560 --> 00:04:08,080
So I'm going to take three vectors, u, v, and w,

69
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:11,000
and take their combinations.

70
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,920
So my u is going to be, they're carefully chosen,

71
00:04:14,920 --> 00:04:20,440
my u is going to be 1 minus 1, 0.

72
00:04:20,440 --> 00:04:23,600
And I'll take vectors in three dimensions.

73
00:04:23,600 --> 00:04:25,960
So that means their combinations will be in three

74
00:04:25,960 --> 00:04:29,960
dimensions, r3, three-dimensional space.

75
00:04:29,960 --> 00:04:38,440
So that'll be u, and then v, let's take 0, I think, 1

76
00:04:38,440 --> 00:04:40,560
and minus 1.

77
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:41,240
OK.

78
00:04:41,240 --> 00:04:44,800
Suppose I stopped there and took their linear combinations.

79
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:50,160
It's very helpful to see a picture in three-dimensional space.

80
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:52,160
The great thing about linear algebra,

81
00:04:52,160 --> 00:04:55,880
it moves into n-dimensional space, 10-dimensional,

82
00:04:55,880 --> 00:04:58,400
100-dimensional, where we can't visualize.

83
00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:02,120
But yet, our instinct is right if we just follow.

84
00:05:02,120 --> 00:05:07,040
So what's your instinct if I took those two vectors,

85
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:09,360
and notice they're not on the same line.

86
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:11,000
One isn't a multiple of the other.

87
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,320
They go in different directions.

88
00:05:13,320 --> 00:05:20,400
If I took their combinations, cx1 times u plus x2 times v,

89
00:05:20,400 --> 00:05:22,240
oh, now let me push.

90
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:24,000
This is a serious question.

91
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:26,680
If I took all their combinations,

92
00:05:26,680 --> 00:05:28,840
so let me try to draw a little bit.

93
00:05:28,840 --> 00:05:33,560
OK, I'm in three-dimensional space, and u goes somewhere,

94
00:05:33,560 --> 00:05:39,080
maybe there, and v goes somewhere, maybe here.

95
00:05:39,080 --> 00:05:42,040
Now suppose I take all the combinations,

96
00:05:42,040 --> 00:05:44,960
so I could multiply that first guy by any number.

97
00:05:44,960 --> 00:05:46,920
That would fill the line.

98
00:05:46,920 --> 00:05:50,840
I could multiply that second guy, v, so this was u,

99
00:05:50,840 --> 00:05:51,960
and this was v.

100
00:05:51,960 --> 00:05:54,240
I could multiply that by any number x2.

101
00:05:54,240 --> 00:05:56,360
That would fill its line.

102
00:05:56,360 --> 00:05:58,120
Each of those lines I would later

103
00:05:58,120 --> 00:06:01,560
call a one-dimensional subspace, just a line.

104
00:06:01,560 --> 00:06:06,800
But now what happens if I take all combinations of the two?

105
00:06:06,800 --> 00:06:08,640
What do you think?

106
00:06:08,640 --> 00:06:09,920
You get a plane.

107
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:11,120
Get a plane.

108
00:06:11,120 --> 00:06:14,480
If I take anything on this line and anything on this line

109
00:06:14,480 --> 00:06:19,480
and add them up, you can see that I'm not going to fill 3d.

110
00:06:19,480 --> 00:06:23,680
But I'm going to fill a plane, and that maybe

111
00:06:23,680 --> 00:06:25,680
takes a little thinking.

112
00:06:25,680 --> 00:06:28,920
It just then becomes sort of, yeah, you see

113
00:06:28,920 --> 00:06:31,240
that that's what it has to be.

114
00:06:31,240 --> 00:06:35,080
OK, now I'm going to have a third vector.

115
00:06:35,080 --> 00:06:39,560
My third vector will be 001.

116
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:44,720
So that 001 is 0 in the x, 0 in the y, and 1 in the z direction.

117
00:06:44,720 --> 00:06:47,000
So there's w.

118
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:51,480
OK, now I want to take their combinations.

119
00:06:51,480 --> 00:06:54,560
OK, so let me do that very specifically.

120
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:56,400
How do I take combinations?

121
00:06:56,400 --> 00:06:58,600
Ha, this is important.

122
00:06:58,600 --> 00:07:01,720
Seems it's very simple but important.

123
00:07:01,720 --> 00:07:07,800
I like to think of taking the combinations of some vectors.

124
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:12,080
I'm always putting vectors into the columns of a matrix.

125
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:15,240
So now I'm going to move to step two, matrix.

126
00:07:15,240 --> 00:07:19,080
I'm going to move to step two, and maybe I'll put it,

127
00:07:19,080 --> 00:07:20,800
well, now I better put it here.

128
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:26,440
OK, step two is the matrix has those vectors in its columns.

129
00:07:26,440 --> 00:07:31,320
So in this case, it's 3 by 3.

130
00:07:31,320 --> 00:07:36,520
OK, that's my matrix that I'm going to call it a.

131
00:07:36,560 --> 00:07:43,120
And now I'm going to, how do I take combinations of vectors?

132
00:07:43,120 --> 00:07:47,880
Well, I could have, I should have maybe done it in detail here,

133
00:07:47,880 --> 00:07:52,800
but let me, I'll just do it with a matrix here.

134
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:54,880
Watch this now.

135
00:07:54,880 --> 00:08:05,000
If I multiply a by the vector of x's, what that does?

136
00:08:05,040 --> 00:08:08,120
So this is now a times x, so very important,

137
00:08:08,120 --> 00:08:10,200
of matrix times a vector.

138
00:08:10,200 --> 00:08:12,600
What does it do?

139
00:08:12,600 --> 00:08:15,720
The output is just what I want.

140
00:08:15,720 --> 00:08:17,840
This is the output.

141
00:08:17,840 --> 00:08:23,000
It takes x1 times the first column, plus x2 times the second,

142
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:24,440
plus x3 times the third.

143
00:08:24,440 --> 00:08:28,840
That's the way matrix multiplication works by columns.

144
00:08:28,840 --> 00:08:30,840
And you don't always see that.

145
00:08:30,840 --> 00:08:32,960
Because what do you see, you know how to,

146
00:08:32,960 --> 00:08:35,960
probably know how to multiply that matrix by that vector.

147
00:08:35,960 --> 00:08:38,320
Let me ask you to do it.

148
00:08:38,320 --> 00:08:40,520
OK, what do you get?

149
00:08:40,520 --> 00:08:43,800
So everybody does it, a component at a time.

150
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:47,440
So what's the first component of the answer?

151
00:08:47,440 --> 00:08:48,520
x1, yeah.

152
00:08:48,520 --> 00:08:49,800
How do you get that?

153
00:08:49,800 --> 00:08:52,840
It's a row times the vector.

154
00:08:52,840 --> 00:08:56,640
And when I say times, I really mean that dot product.

155
00:08:56,640 --> 00:09:00,000
This time plus this, plus this is x1.

156
00:09:00,040 --> 00:09:01,760
And what about the second row?

157
00:09:04,760 --> 00:09:09,760
Minus x1 plus x2, or I'll just say x2 minus x1.

158
00:09:09,760 --> 00:09:16,360
And the third guy, the third component would be x3 minus x2.

159
00:09:16,360 --> 00:09:19,200
Right?

160
00:09:19,200 --> 00:09:22,040
OK.

161
00:09:22,040 --> 00:09:25,760
So right away, I'm going to say, I'm going to call this

162
00:09:25,760 --> 00:09:27,880
matrix a, a difference matrix.

163
00:09:27,920 --> 00:09:31,440
It always helps to give names to things.

164
00:09:31,440 --> 00:09:34,480
So this a is a difference matrix.

165
00:09:34,480 --> 00:09:37,440
Because it takes differences of the x's.

166
00:09:37,440 --> 00:09:40,440
And I would even say a first difference matrix.

167
00:09:40,440 --> 00:09:43,840
Because it's just a straightforward difference.

168
00:09:43,840 --> 00:09:48,080
And we'll see second differences in class Friday.

169
00:09:48,080 --> 00:09:48,800
OK.

170
00:09:48,800 --> 00:09:50,080
So that's what a does.

171
00:09:50,080 --> 00:09:54,120
But remember my first point was that when a matrix

172
00:09:54,120 --> 00:09:58,600
multiplies a vector, the result is a combination

173
00:09:58,600 --> 00:10:01,560
of the columns.

174
00:10:01,560 --> 00:10:04,800
And that's not always, because see, I'm looking at the

175
00:10:04,800 --> 00:10:07,120
picture, not just by numbers.

176
00:10:07,120 --> 00:10:10,880
You know, with numbers I'm just doing this stuff.

177
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:13,880
But now I'm stepping back a little bit and saying, I'm

178
00:10:13,880 --> 00:10:18,120
combining, it's this vector times x1.

179
00:10:18,120 --> 00:10:22,200
That vector times x1 plus this vector times x2 plus that one

180
00:10:22,200 --> 00:10:25,720
times x3 added together gives me this.

181
00:10:25,720 --> 00:10:28,800
Same, nothing complicated here.

182
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:31,680
Just look at it by vectors also.

183
00:10:31,680 --> 00:10:32,440
OK.

184
00:10:32,440 --> 00:10:39,040
Now suppose, so, so, it's a little interesting already.

185
00:10:39,040 --> 00:10:45,000
Here we multiplied these vectors by numbers.

186
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:46,840
x1, x2, x3.

187
00:10:46,840 --> 00:10:49,120
That was our thinking here.

188
00:10:49,120 --> 00:10:52,400
Now our thinking here is a little, we've switched slightly.

189
00:10:52,400 --> 00:10:57,840
Now I'm multiplying the matrix times the numbers in x.

190
00:10:57,840 --> 00:10:59,200
Just a slight switch.

191
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:01,160
Multiply the matrix times the numbers.

192
00:11:01,160 --> 00:11:03,200
And I get some answer, b.

193
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:04,040
Which is this?

194
00:11:04,040 --> 00:11:05,840
This is b.

195
00:11:05,840 --> 00:11:07,520
OK.

196
00:11:07,520 --> 00:11:07,880
OK.

197
00:11:07,880 --> 00:11:12,640
And of course I can do a specific example like, suppose I

198
00:11:12,640 --> 00:11:19,920
take, well, I could take the squares to be in x.

199
00:11:19,920 --> 00:11:27,880
So suppose I take a times the first three squares, 1, 4, 9.

200
00:11:27,880 --> 00:11:29,960
What answer would I get?

201
00:11:29,960 --> 00:11:35,120
Just to keep it clear that we're very specific here.

202
00:11:35,120 --> 00:11:38,680
So what would be the output b?

203
00:11:38,680 --> 00:11:42,240
I think of this as the input, the 1, 4, 9, the x's.

204
00:11:42,360 --> 00:11:46,520
Now the machine is a multiply by a.

205
00:11:46,520 --> 00:11:48,280
And here's the output.

206
00:11:48,280 --> 00:11:49,680
And what would be the output?

207
00:11:49,680 --> 00:11:51,360
What numbers am I going to get there?

208
00:11:51,360 --> 00:11:52,840
Yeah.

209
00:11:52,840 --> 00:11:55,160
1, 3, something?

210
00:11:55,160 --> 00:11:57,840
1, 3, 5.

211
00:11:57,840 --> 00:12:03,240
Which is actually a little neat that you find the differences

212
00:12:03,240 --> 00:12:06,080
of the squares are the odd numbers.

213
00:12:06,080 --> 00:12:09,960
That appealed to me in school somehow.

214
00:12:09,960 --> 00:12:13,480
And that was already a bad sign, right?

215
00:12:13,480 --> 00:12:18,520
This dumb kid notices that you take differences of squares

216
00:12:18,520 --> 00:12:19,560
and you get odd numbers.

217
00:12:19,560 --> 00:12:20,040
Right.

218
00:12:20,040 --> 00:12:20,920
Whatever.

219
00:12:20,920 --> 00:12:21,880
OK.

220
00:12:21,880 --> 00:12:25,280
So now is a big step.

221
00:12:25,280 --> 00:12:29,400
This was the forward direction.

222
00:12:29,400 --> 00:12:32,040
Input, and there's the output.

223
00:12:32,040 --> 00:12:36,520
But now the real reality, that's easy and important.

224
00:12:36,520 --> 00:12:47,240
But the more deep problem is, what if I give you b and ask

225
00:12:47,240 --> 00:12:48,360
for x?

226
00:12:48,360 --> 00:12:52,240
So again, we're switching the direction here.

227
00:12:52,240 --> 00:12:52,560
OK.

228
00:12:52,560 --> 00:12:55,680
We're solving an equation now, or three equations,

229
00:12:55,680 --> 00:12:58,160
and three unknowns, ax equal b.

230
00:12:58,160 --> 00:13:02,640
So if I give you this b, can you get x?

231
00:13:02,640 --> 00:13:03,040
OK.

232
00:13:03,040 --> 00:13:04,960
How do you solve three equations?

233
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:08,000
So it's just we're looking backwards.

234
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:13,200
Now, that won't be too hard for this matrix,

235
00:13:13,200 --> 00:13:16,160
for this particular matrix that I chose.

236
00:13:16,160 --> 00:13:20,480
Because it's triangular, we'll be able to find,

237
00:13:20,480 --> 00:13:23,240
we'll be able to go backwards.

238
00:13:23,240 --> 00:13:25,960
So let me do that.

239
00:13:25,960 --> 00:13:28,480
Let me take b to b.

240
00:13:28,480 --> 00:13:29,760
It's a vector.

241
00:13:29,760 --> 00:13:31,640
It's got three components.

242
00:13:31,640 --> 00:13:36,200
And now I'm going to go backwards to find x.

243
00:13:36,200 --> 00:13:38,120
Or we will.

244
00:13:38,120 --> 00:13:39,440
OK.

245
00:13:39,440 --> 00:13:41,960
So do you see the three equations?

246
00:13:41,960 --> 00:13:47,880
Here they are, x1 is b1, this is b2, that difference is b3.

247
00:13:47,880 --> 00:13:49,280
Those are my three equations.

248
00:13:49,280 --> 00:13:53,240
Three unknown x's, three known right-hand sides.

249
00:13:53,240 --> 00:13:58,560
Or I think of it as a times x is a matrix times x giving a

250
00:13:58,560 --> 00:14:00,520
vector b.

251
00:14:00,520 --> 00:14:02,080
What's the answer?

252
00:14:02,080 --> 00:14:05,680
OK, as I said, we're going to be able to do this.

253
00:14:05,680 --> 00:14:09,160
We're going to be able to solve this system easily because

254
00:14:09,160 --> 00:14:11,840
it's already triangular.

255
00:14:11,840 --> 00:14:14,520
And it's actually lower triangular.

256
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:17,920
So that means we'll start from the top.

257
00:14:17,920 --> 00:14:24,760
So the answer is the solution will be what?

258
00:14:24,760 --> 00:14:26,160
Let's make room for it.

259
00:14:26,160 --> 00:14:28,880
x1, x2, and x3.

260
00:14:28,880 --> 00:14:30,480
I want to find.

261
00:14:30,480 --> 00:14:33,880
And what's the answer?

262
00:14:33,880 --> 00:14:37,520
Can we just go from top to bottom now?

263
00:14:37,520 --> 00:14:40,560
